{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539292"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16567"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16567"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.03,0,0.95,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9258"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9258"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51155"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"660"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5931"},{"type":"tags","id":"10357"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44970"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of episodes of severe vertigo lasting 10-30 seconds. The episodes are triggered by rolling over in bed, looking up, or bending down. She has no hearing loss, tinnitus, or headache. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Otoscopy reveals normal tympanic membranes bilaterally. There is no spontaneous nystagmus. Cranial nerve examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Meniere disease","Vestibular neuritis","Acoustic neuroma","Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo","Mal de debarquement syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is classic for benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV). \u003Cstrong\u003EBenign paroxysmal positional vertigo\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by brief episodes of vertigo triggered by changes in head position, particularly when lying down, rolling over in bed, or looking up. The pathophysiology involves displaced otoconia (calcium carbonate crystals) from the utricle entering the semicircular canals, most commonly the posterior canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with episodes of vertigo lasting hours, accompanied by fluctuating hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness. These episodes are not positionally triggered, and the duration is much longer than in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with acute onset constant vertigo lasting days to weeks, often preceded by a viral illness. The vertigo is not positional, and patients typically have significant nausea and vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcoustic neuroma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with gradual, progressive unilateral hearing loss and tinnitus. Vertigo is not a prominent feature, and when present, it is not characteristically positional.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMal de debarquement syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a sensation of rocking or swaying that persists after exposure to motion (typically after sea travel). It is constant rather than episodic and not triggered by position changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of BPPV can be confirmed with the Dix-Hallpike manoeuvre, which will typically elicit brief vertigo and characteristic nystagmus. Treatment involves canalith repositioning manoeuvres, such as the Epley manoeuvre, which are highly effective in resolving symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) is characterised by brief episodes of vertigo triggered by head movement.","BPPV is caused by otoconia (calcium carbonate crystals) becoming dislodged from the utricle and entering the semicircular canals.","The Dix-Hallpike manoeuvre is the diagnostic test of choice for posterior canal BPPV."],"references":["Dommaraju S, Perera E. An approach to vertigo in general practice. Aust Fam Physician. 2016 Apr;45(4):190-4. PMID: 27052132.","You P, Instrum R, Parnes L. Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo. Laryngoscope Investig Otolaryngol. 2018 Dec 14;4(1):116-123. doi: 10.1002/lio2.230. PMID: 30828628; PMCID: PMC6383320.","Hornibrook J. Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV): History, Pathophysiology, Office Treatment and Future Directions. Int J Otolaryngol. 2011;2011:835671. doi: 10.1155/2011/835671. Epub 2011 Jul 25. PMID: 21808648; PMCID: PMC3144715.","Palmeri R, Kumar A. Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo. 2022 Dec 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29261987."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51155"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16567"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51155"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T17:52:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T10:17:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9258"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":